1.4.4. Create coulmn for the approximate estimated distance from latitude and longitude¶

In [108]:
# create a function to calculate distance 
def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2, to_radians=True, earth_radius=6371):
    
    if to_radians:
        lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = np.radians([lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])

    a = np.sin((lat2-lat1)/2.0)**2 + \
        np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin((lon2-lon1)/2.0)**2

    return earth_radius * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
# create column for approximate distance from start to end.
bike['app_distance_km'] = haversine(bike.start_station_latitude, bike.start_station_longitude, bike.end_station_latitude, bike.end_station_longitude)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 raws data trips for fordgobike in the dataset with 16 Coulmns (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude ,end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip), with a missing values in (start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, member_birth_year, member_gender).

In this data coulmns features divded into a trip duration information(in duration_sec, start_time, end_time), station information(in start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude),and member information (in bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip).

What is the Cleanning of your dataset?¶

  • Removing the null values in start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, member_birth_year, member_gender to be 175147 raws data in dataset.
  • coulmns with a object data type to be in a suitable data type.
  • changing the time to be in datetime.

What is the additional information for your dataset?¶

which Hour of the day, day of the week, and month of year the member start its trip? to add:

  • start_hour , start_day.

The age of the member in 2020 to add:

  • age

estimated distance takes by member in the trip by latitude and longitude to add:

  • app_distance_km , app_distance_in_m

the duration in minute to be easy in estimation.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature interist is the duration of the trip alone with how related to the member information or characteristics, to answer the questions

  • Is the age is an important factor in long trips duration?
  • what is the average trips duration takes?
  • Is their any effect of specific Houre or a day to be week end on the trips?
  • the geographical effect on the number of the trips, is their trips in area more than the other?
  • Is their any effect of user subscriber or customer?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • the trip starting time to know the average of the trips takes
  • the main gender or group of people to ride
  • the main areas that you can traget
  • any special pattern associated with a specific group of riders.

# the Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Subscribers
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
subscribers = bike.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
s = subscribers.groupby(['start_day', 'start_hour']).size()
s = s.reset_index(name='count')
s = s.pivot(index='start_day', columns='start_hour', values='count')
sb.heatmap(s, cmap='Blues');
plt.title('Subscribers', loc='left');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');
# the Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Customers
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
customers = bike.query('user_type == "Customer"')
c = customers.groupby(['start_day', 'start_hour']).size()
c = c.reset_index(name='count')
c = c.pivot(index='start_day', columns='start_hour', values='count')
sb.heatmap(c, cmap='Blues');
plt.title('Customer', loc='left');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');

  • For customers: Have the same features of the Subscribers in number of the riders oncentated in (Mon-to-Fri)in the same rush houres like subscribers, but for weekends (sat, sun) theirs also a densty in the graph between 9:30 to 17:00.
